s of the Biblical Sources -- tIn Search of the Original Biblical Record of the Assyrian Conquest of Samaria -- tPart V: Working with the Book of Kings: the Chronological Framework -- t2 Kings 15–18: a Chronological Conundrum? -- tThe Last Days of Israel: Chronological Considerations -- tPart VI: Working with the Book of Kings: the Narrative -- tWicked Usurpers and the Doom of Samaria. Further Views on the Angle of 2 Kings 15–17 -- tHoshea ben Elah, the Last King of Israel: Narrative and History in 2 Kings 17:1–6 -- tDid Hoshea of Israel Continue the Foreign Policy of His Predecessors? -- tPart VII: Reflections in the Prophets -- tThe Book of Hosea and the Last Days of the Northern Kingdom. The Methodological Problem -- tIsaiah and the Fall of the Kingdom of Israel -- tIndices -- t1. General index -- t2. Words -- t3. Texts0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aDespite considerable scholarly efforts for many years, the last two decades of the Kingdom of Israel are still beneath the veil of history. What was the status of the Kingdom after its annexation by Assyria in 732 BCE? Who conquered Samaria, the capital of the Kingdom? When did it happen? One of the primary reasons for this situation lies in the discrepancies found in the historical sources, namely the Hebrew Bible and the Assyrian texts. Since biblical studies and Assyriology are two distinct disciplines, the gaps in the sources are not easy to bridge. Moreover, recent great progress in the archaeological research in the Southern Levant provides now crucial new data, independent of these textual sources. This volume, a collection of papers by leading scholars from different fields of research, aims to bring together, for the first time, all the available data and to discuss these conundrums from various perspectives in order to reach a better and deeper understanding of this crucial period, which possibly triggered in the following decades the birth of "new Israel" in the Southern Kingdom of Judah, and eventually led to the formation of the Hebrew Bible and its underlying theology.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 04. Okt 2022) 0aAssyro-Babylonian literaturexHistory and criticism. 0aJewsxHistoryy953-586 B.C. 4aAssyrisches Reich. 4aHosea. 4aKönigreich Israel. 4aSamarien. 7aRELIGION / Ancient.2bisacsh  aHoshea.  aKingdom of Israel.  aNeo-Assyria.  aSamaria.1 aBecking, Bob, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFales, Frederick Mario, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFrahm, Eckart, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFranklin, Norma, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFrevel, Christian, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHasegawa, Shuichi, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHasegawa, Shuichi, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aHentschel, Georg, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKahn, Dan’el, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLevin, Christoph, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLevin, Christoph, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aMcKenzie, Steven L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMorkot, Robert G., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNissinen, Martti, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNovotny, Jamie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPietsch, Michael, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRadner, Karen